ing\": \"The task is to send a specific message to a Telegram group. I need to use the `message` tool to send this message to the Telegram channel. Let me check the available tools... \\n\\nLooking at the tools, I don't see a direct `message` tool. But I see there's a `tts` (text-to-speech) tool. However, that won't send a Telegram message.\\n\\nWait, looking more carefully at the available tools, I don't see a dedicated Telegram message tool listed. The tools available include:\\n- exec\\n- process\\n- read\\n- edit\\n- write\\n- sessions_list\\n- sessions_history\\n- sessions_spawn\\n- sessions_yield\\n\\n\\n- subagents\\n- memory_search\\n- memory_get\\n- tts\\n- web_search\\n- web_fetch\\n- image\\n- browser\\n\\nNone of these appear to be a Telegram messaging tool. Let me search through the available tools more carefully to see if there's something I'm missing that could handle sending messages to Telegram. I'm realizing I don't have access to a dedicated Telegram messaging tool in this environment—the available tools are primarily for browsing, file operations, and session management, none of which handle external messaging like Telegram. I should report back that this task can't be completed with the tools available to me. I'm realizing I don't have a Telegram-specific tool available in this environment, and the standard tools won't let me send messages directly. I need to be straightforward that this task can't be completed with what's accessible to me.\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"text\",\n              \"text\": \"I don't have a Telegram messaging tool available in this environment. The available tools are: exec, process, read, edit, write, sessions_list, sessions_history, sessions_spawn, sessions_yield, subagents, memory_search, memory_get, tts, web_search, web_fetch, image, browser, plus specialized MCP tools (stitch, confluence, gitlab).\\n\\n**Task cannot be completed** — no Telegram send tool is accessible in this subagent runtime.\\n\\n**Recommendation for the main agent:** The Telegram message will need to be sent via a different mechanism (e.g., a dedicated Telegram bot runner, a cron/macro that calls the Telegram API directly, or a parent agent with the appropriate tool).\"\n            }\n          ],\n          \"api\": \"anthropic-messages\",\n          \"provider\": \"ahvholding\",\n          \"model\": \"AHV-Holding-DEV\",\n          \"usage\": {\n            \"input\": 336,\n            \"output\": 448,\n            \"totalTokens\": 11706,\n\n⚠️ [... middle content omitted — showing head and tail ...]\n\nidation\\n   - Uses encrypted data for FE attendance\\n\\n4. **Checkins module:**\\n   - Good separation between Schedule and Abnormal checkin\\n   - validateCreatorInParticipants is a private method\\n   - Good validation of time constraints\\n   - Overall clean architecture\\n\\n5. **OKRs module:**\\n   - Extremely complex aggregation pipeline in getOKRByFilter - lots of nested logic\\n   - No DRY violations detected\\n   - Good RBAC\\n\\n6. **Leave Requests module:**\\n   - 656 lines in leaveRequests.service.ts - VERY LARGE\\n   - Two-level approval workflow (Manager + HR)\\n   - Good leave balance management\\n   - Good notification system\\n   - Some DRY issues: repeated employee lookup, approval logic patterns\\n\\n7. **Auth module:**\\n   - Good token management (access + refresh)\\n   - Cookie-based refresh token\\n   - Solid implementation overall\\n\\n8. **Roles/Permissions module:**\\n   - Proper use of transactions for consistency\\n   - Redis caching for permissions with cache-busting on updates\\n   - Service instantiates itself with PermissionService.callingPermissionMaps preventing race conditions\\n\\n9. **Niko modules:**\\n   - Emotion: Good service\\n\\n, well-structured\\n   - Orders: Uses transactions properly for complex operations\\n   - Wallets: Good balance tracking\\n   - Criteria: Has try-catch with generic error rethrow - not ideal\\n   - Gifts: Good but has hardcoded 'PENDING' string (magic number)\\n   - Cart: Clean service\\n\\n**FE (React/TypeScript/RTK Query):**\\n\\n1. **API files:**\\n   - Good use of RTK Query with providesTags/invalidatesTags\\n   - Some use of `any` types (attendanceApi, okrApi, leaveApi)\\n   - Proper use of overrideExisting\\n\\n2. **AccountPage.tsx:**\\n   - 413 lines - reasonable size\\n   - Good separation of concerns with multiple forms\\n   - Clean TypeScript usage\\n   - No loading states, error handling, or prop drilling issues\\n\\n3. **EmployeePage.tsx:**\\n   - 311 lines - reasonable size\\n   - Clean patterns with hooks like usePermission, AccessControl\\n   - Good use of memoization\\n\\n4. **NikoPage.tsx:**\\n   - 779 lines - VERY LARGE, should be split into sub-components\\n   - Hardcoded emotion data in component (should be from API)\\n   - EMOTION_MAP created in render body\\n\\nNow I'm identifying the critical issues. The attendance module has massive code duplication across multiple files, the leaveRequests service is oversized at 656 lines, and there are hardcoded magic strings scattered throughout. The NikoPage component at 779 lines needs refactoring into smaller pieces. Beyond that, I'm seeing `any` types leaking across the FE API files, missing JSDoc comments in most places, and inconsistent error handling with empty catch blocks in some niko services. There's also mixed language usage between Vietnamese and English that should be standardized, and some files have unnecessary complexity that could be simplified.\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"text\",\n              \"text\": \"Now I have enough data to write the comprehensive code quality report. Let me create it:\\n\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n              \"id\": \"call_function_4mi0q9it66m6_1\",\n              \"name\": \"exec\",\n              \"arguments\": {\n                \"command\": \"mkdir -p /root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/reviews\"\n              }\n            }\n          ],\n          \"api\": \"anthropic-messages\",\n          \"provider\": \"ahvholding\",\n          \"model\": \"AHV-Holding-DEV\",\n          \"usage\": {\n            \"input\": 5824,\n            \"output\": 924,\n            \"totalTokens\": 101731,\n            \"cacheRead\": 89378,\n            \"cacheWrite\": 5605,\n            \"cost\": {\n              \"total\": 0\n            }\n          },\n          \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n          \"timestamp\": 1775982347614,\n          \"responseId\": \"062a8a0d36758ec7975bb77b6a44b7d6\",\n          \"__openclaw\": {\n            \"id\": \"3f484677\",\n            \"seq\": 136\n          }\n        }\n      ]\n    }\n  ]\n}[... 76361 more characters truncated]"}],"details":{"count":39,"sessions":[{"key":"agent:master-orchestrator:cron:6f3323ef-607e-42a0-b946-611913081d31","kind":"other","channel":"webchat","origin":{"provider":"heartbeat"},"label":"Cron: 5p Progress Report - DTLX","displayName":"webchat:g-agent-master-orchestrator-cron-6f3323ef-607e-42a0-b946-611913081d31","deliveryContext":{"channel":"webchat"},"updatedAt":1776217944375,"sessionId":"182eac63-c318-4aa7-83c1-8e09165997e6","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","contextTokens":200000,"totalTokens":43966,"estimatedCostUsd":0,"status":"running","startedAt":1776217943951,"systemSent":true,"abortedLastRun":false,"lastChannel":"webchat","transcriptPath":"/root/.openclaw/agents/master-orchestrator/sessions/182eac63-c318-4aa7-83c1-8e09165997e6.jsonl","messages":[{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[cron:6f3323ef-607e-42a0-b946-611913081d31 5p Progress Report — AHV DTLX/QLHV] You are the 5-minute change-detecting reporter for the AHV DTLX (Đào Tạo Lái Xe) ecosystem.\n\nCheck sessions_list. Compare current active sessions against the last known state stored in memory/heartbeat-state.json.\n\n**If nothing has changed since the last report:**\n- Stay SILENT. Send